+ What the contract does:
+ Tracks contributions per address in a mapping. Whoever has contributed the most
  becomes owner via contribute(), capped at under 0.001 ether per call. The owner
  can call withdraw() to drain the entire contract balance.

+ The vulnerability:
+ The receive() fallback reassigns ownership based on a weak, disconnected check —
  it only requires contributions[msg.sender] > 0, not that the sender is the
  highest contributor. Any account that has contributed even 1 wei can become
  owner simply by sending ETH directly to the contract.

+ How I exploited it:
+ Called await contract.contribute({ value: 1 }) to satisfy contributions[msg.sender] > 0,
  then sent a plain transaction directly to the contract address via
  web3.eth.sendTransaction({ to: contract.address, value: ... }), triggering
  receive() and setting owner = player. Finally called await contract.withdraw()
  to drain the contract balance.

+ Impact:
+ Complete loss of funds and total compromise of the ownership model — any
  external account can become owner for negligible cost and drain the contract.

+ Fix:
+ Never mutate privileged state like owner inside receive()/fallback(). Ownership
  transfer should go through an explicit, access-controlled function (e.g.
  transferOwnership() restricted by onlyOwner).
